<div id="review_3652980085" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3652980085" />
    <a title="Michael Berens" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76436654-michael-berens"><img alt="Michael Berens" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1528989964p2/76436654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3652980085?book_show_action=true">Dec 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Berens" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Berens" href="/user/show/76436654-michael-berens">Michael Berens</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12352836-piers-the-ploughman">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76436654-michael-berens?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/76436654-michael-berens?shelf=religion">religion</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3652980085" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16942227009540277621">Although &quot;Piers Ploughman&quot; is often compared to Dante&apos;s &quot;Divine Comedy&quot; or Bunyan&apos;s &quot;Pilgrim&apos;s Progress,&quot; it reminded me of the English medieval mystery play &quot;Everyman&quot; in its use of allegorical figures to represent various human virtues and vices and its aim to explore what it means to live a good life. This is a prose translation, so one misses the music of Langland&apos;s verse. However, it is much more accessible for the reader not schooled in Middle English and highly readable. I enjoyed the ear</span>
  <span id="freeText16942227009540277621" style="display:none">Although "Piers Ploughman" is often compared to Dante's "Divine Comedy" or Bunyan's "Pilgrim's Progress," it reminded me of the English medieval mystery play "Everyman" in its use of allegorical figures to represent various human virtues and vices and its aim to explore what it means to live a good life. This is a prose translation, so one misses the music of Langland's verse. However, it is much more accessible for the reader not schooled in Middle English and highly readable. I enjoyed the earlier sections of the poem, in which Langland satirizes human vices and the corruption within the Church, more than the later sections, which re-tell the life and Passion of Jesus from the Gospels and summarize Church doctrine relating to such matters as the forgiveness of sins, the nature of the Trinity and the sacrament of Holy Communion. The poem has been described as a proto-Protestant document, with its emphasis on the individual conscience and experience of divine truth, as well as for its criticism of the clergy and such practices as the selling of indulgences. At the end, Langland makes a plea for a purified and unified Church. One wonders what he would have made of the schism that occurred as a result of the Reformation. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16942227009540277621" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

