<div id="review_3758704180" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3758704180" />
    <a title="Steve R" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51602729-steve-r"><img alt="Steve R" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1550608435p2/51602729.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3758704180?book_show_action=true">Jan 09, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve R" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve R" href="/user/show/51602729-steve-r">Steve R</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3758704180" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12008121864519420286">I read this late fourteenth century allegorical poem almost half a century ago, and in my fractured memory today, it is almost completely conflated with my impressions of Bunyan&apos;s <i>Pilgrim&apos;s Progress</i>. Also like a lot of Chaucer&apos;s original writings and translations, allegory seems to have been a natural sort of fall back for writers of this time, and the omnipresent vision of a life consumed by religious values and moral concerns gets a little heavy handed at times. Patience, Charity and Hope are </span>
  <span id="freeText12008121864519420286" style="display:none">I read this late fourteenth century allegorical poem almost half a century ago, and in my fractured memory today, it is almost completely conflated with my impressions of Bunyan's <i>Pilgrim's Progress</i>. Also like a lot of Chaucer's original writings and translations, allegory seems to have been a natural sort of fall back for writers of this time, and the omnipresent vision of a life consumed by religious values and moral concerns gets a little heavy handed at times. Patience, Charity and Hope are all worthy ideals, but any book that includes a chapter entitled 'The Confession of the Seven Deadly Sins and the Search for Truth' is one I'm going to read more for what it said about the circumscribed imaginations which existed socially and culturally at the time than for any call to better myself. I much prefer the relativism of modern times to the strait jacket of morality imposed by cultures which took religion far too seriously for my taste.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12008121864519420286" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

